President Obama met with members of the Congressional Black Caucus (CBC) to discuss various topics including the economy, voting rights legislation, education, immigration reform, youth employment, gun violence, and anti-poverty programs. The President emphasized the importance of education, from early education to college affordability. He expressed disappointment with the Supreme Court's decision on the Voting Rights Act and reaffirmed his commitment to address voter discrimination. The President and the CBC expressed frustration with the pace of economic growth and unemployment rates among African Americans. They discussed the need to reduce gun violence and promote the benefits of the Affordable Care Act. The meeting concluded with the President thanking the CBC and expressing his desire to continue working with them.